# FAQ

Practical answers for learners using this guide to prepare for the Claude Certified Architect — Foundations exam.

## About the exam

### What is the CCA Foundations exam?

Anthropic's entry-level certification for solution architects who design and build production applications with Claude. It validates practical judgment across the Claude Agent SDK, the Claude API, Claude Code, and the Model Context Protocol (MCP).

### What's the format?

60 multiple-choice questions. Each question has one correct answer and three distractors. Unanswered questions are scored as incorrect. The exam is scenario-based: 4 of 6 scenarios are selected at random, and each scenario frames a set of questions.

### What's the passing score and time limit?

720 out of 1000, scaled. The scaled score adjusts for form-to-form difficulty differences, so you do not literally need 72% correct. On this repo's practice exam, aim for 90%+ in Exam Mode before you schedule the real exam. Time limit is 120 minutes.

### What does the exam cost?

Free at the time of writing.

### Do I need to write code during the exam?

No. You will *read* Python, bash, and JSON fluently — recognizing correct implementations vs anti-patterns in code shown in questions — but you will not write code. Every question is multiple choice.

### How do I register?

[Anthropic's registration page](https://anthropic.skilljar.com/claude-certified-architect-foundations-access-request).

## Using this guide

### What's the intended order?

Work Modules 1 → 5 in order. Each lab is ~20 minutes. After the Final Capstone, take the Practice Exam in Exam Mode. If any domain scores below 80%, re-read those labs and retake the exam.

### Can I skip labs on topics I already know?

The Check-Your-Understanding questions and Anti-pattern blocks are where most exam-relevant details live. A concept you think you understand may have a wrong-answer trap you haven't internalized yet — the labs are short enough that skimming them costs little and catches gaps you didn't know you had.

### How do I know I'm ready?

Three criteria: (1) you complete all 31 labs including the capstone, (2) you score 900+ on the Practice Exam in Exam Mode, and (3) for any domain below 90%, you can close your eyes and recite the two or three hardest anti-patterns without prompting. If all three hold, schedule the exam.

### What if a domain scores low on the practice exam?

Start with the [Anti-Patterns Cheat Sheet](#anti-patterns-cheat-sheet) entries for that domain. Each entry links back to the lab that teaches the pattern. Re-read the lab, redo its Check-Your-Understanding questions, then retry the practice exam. Most domain weaknesses resolve with one focused re-read.

### How long should it take?

Roughly 10–12 hours of focused work across the labs, plus 1–2 hours for the Practice Exam. Most learners spread this across 2–3 weeks.

## About this course

### How does this compare to claudecertifications.com?

The reference site summarizes each domain in 3–4 subsections. This repo maps 1:1 to all 30 official task statements from Anthropic's OG Exam Guide, with worked Python code and Q&A drills for each. Our content is broader and more technically specific; the reference site has some framing tools this repo does not (e.g., narrative walkthroughs for all 6 scenarios — see [Scenario 2](#scenario-2-code-generation-with-claude-code) for one of them here).

### Where does the canonical exam content live?

The [OG Exam Guide](OG Exam Guide) in this repo is Anthropic's official exam guide — the authoritative source. When anything in this course or any external reference contradicts the OG Guide, trust the OG Guide.

### Which Claude model do the code examples use?

`claude-sonnet-4-5`. If you are running the examples yourself against the Anthropic API, update the model ID to the latest Sonnet available at the time.

### Where do I report errors or suggest improvements?

Open an issue on [the GitHub repo](https://github.com/kelcorlabs/lab-guide/issues). Include the lab number and a short description of what's wrong or could be clearer.


